PARKING: If you can't find free parking on Lennox Rd, the parking garage behind the store has coin and electronic (website\/parking passport app) options. The parking passport app charges 50¢\/hour rather than the 25¢\/hour that most of the meters charge. Also, there is a 35¢ convenience fee tacked on to each payment. Of note, the first 2 non-handicap spots are more expensive than the rest (50¢\/hour), but they give 30min free.

Great job!
Thumbs up! Always great service, great food, fantastic atmosphere.
Love the desserts & the veggie pakora. The naan is good, as well as the saag dishes. Good buffet, lamb korma is fun, too!
Yummy escargots and oysters Rockefeller! The venison was tender and tasty. The chocolate cake dessert was large enough for 3 people to share, and so decadent!

Cute little place! The Saigon wings were a hit with the kids! Yummy pork in the pork fried rice. The seafood with egg noodles was also devoured by the kids--not spicy at all (which was easily remedied with siracha). The vietnamese crepe was also good. Everything tasted fresh. The staff was attentive and friendly, too!
Shwarma had tender, tasty meat that even my 5 yr old loved, MR spinach pie was yummy! Good cookies & cream milkshake. Kid friendly!
Great homemade ice cream! Uses local ingredients for their special flavors. Amazing maple walnut ice cream. Cute working electric train track on the ceiling!

Good sushi quality, cute little place, but busy even at times you don't expect to be hectic!  Reasonable prices, good portions, nice flavor, and the food tasted fresh! Udon noodles with beef were tasty, as were the eel and avocado rolls and the sushi sashimi combo.  The salmon teriyaki and spicy tuna rolls were great, too.  We were too full, but they have fried ice cream!

Weekend buffet had a great variety, with the usual suspects but also a few less common vegetable dishes. The okra was really good, and the naan was crispy without being burnt.  The chicken tikka masala was a big hit with the kids. The kheer and mango ice cream were fantastic!

Yum!  Great lunch buffet, $9.99 on a Saturday. Several different main dishes, 2 different types of rice, 2 types of naan, several desserts, including yummy homemade mango ice cream!  Loved the veggie korma, saag, mutter paneer, chicken tikka masala!  Attentive staff. Definitely coming by again when I'm in this neck of the woods!
Huge portions, great seafood chimichangas, fun combo appetizer. Family friendly! Broken freezer = no fried ice cream. Kids eat free on Sun!

They have hand pulled noodles!  The Bejing Zha Jiang noodles are similar to Ja Jang Myun, and were satisfying. My friend said the chicken and mushroom hand pulled noodles were good, and she loved the mango soup dessert item--looked like there were tapioca pearls in it. We have come here twice so far for our noodle  fix!

A little pricey, but free and ample parking right outside.  Yummy bread for the table, especially one with seeds baked in the bread. The pasta was rich and tasty, and the portion was large enough that I brought some home. The artichoke dip was good, but came already placed on top of the bread, so the gluten sensitive member of our party had to scrape it off the bread to eat it.
Lots of fun pickled banchan, and macaroni salad. The japchae and bulgogi were great! The bibimbap was okay, but a little bland. Friendly service!
The pad Thai was good, but had wider noodles and wasn't quite as tangy as I'm used to. Nice crisp veggies and tender chicken, though!  The kids liked the Korean bbq short ribs.
Amazing burgers--so tender and tasty! The burgers are large, so consider getting a little burger. Everything is great with grilled onions and mushrooms. Yummy Cajun fries, too.

Hibachi steak was juicy, shrimp was good, too. The dragon rainbow roll & firecracker roll were just ok. The hibachi show was less elaborate than Benihana's, but still fun. Show ID on your birthday for $12 off and a piece of cheesecake!

The food was pretty good--one of the better restaurants in the area. The service was good and attentive. They have free chips and salsa before the meal. The cheese quesadilla was pretty good, as was the chicken burrito.
Nice selection of breakfast items, friendly service. Got a chikichanga (chicken, avocado, cheese), which was pretty good. Good breakfast nook for families!

East side Indian buffet, decent selection, some Chinese-style items like a noodle dish that looked like Lo Mein. Punjab saag was somewhat bland. The little corn pancakes were good! The opo potatoes were fun and the tandoori chicken and chicken tikka masala were a hit with the kids! Good mango and coconut ice cream, and the kheer was tasty, too.
Large selection, sushi rolls included in the buffet! Particularly liked the fried doughnuts and the kids liked the soft serve ice cream machine. The food is decent, and there's lots of it!

Lots of choices for main dishes, including a goat curry, a few chicken dishes, and several veggie dishes! Mango and pistachio ice cream were really good! The rice pudding had more texture and less moisture than I'm used to. Plenty of fresh naan, and there was enough spice in most dishes to make things interesting! Also a few Asian dishes, like sesame chicken, veggie egg rolls, and lo mein style noodles. Attentive staff!

Tasty Panang curry! The green papaya fries were interesting. Loved the drunken noodles, though they were quite spicy! The pad see eaw was pretty good, but the other dishes were better. The chicken satay was pretty dry. Be sure to order enough rice for the curry!

The rock cooker bibimbap with the sunny side up egg was really good! Pretty authentic chicken with ginseng and galbi tang. The kids liked the bulgogi. Will definitely come back when I'm jonesing for some Korean food!
Cute pay by the oz froyo place! Tons of different toppings from which to choose, including real fruit! Sample anything you like, mix and match different flavors in the same cup if you like!

A bit confusing at first, but a lot of fun and delicious food!  Loved the lamb and the coconut soup base. The Popular Sauce recipe on the sauce buffet was great, especially with a healthy heaping of minced garlic, cilantro, and the spicy sauce! My friend loved the pork, and the kids loved the mushroom soup base.  Ramen and glass noodles on the buffet, all you can eat! Udon noodles a la carte were a hit with the kids. The potatoes took a while to cook, but were yummy! Will definitely come back!

Went on a Pasta Tuesday night - pasta dishes 50% off! Amazing crab lobster artichoke dip, fantastic calamari, and the bread was so good! One of our party declared the lasagna was some of the best she'd had. The ravioli quattro formaggi was gobbled up by the kids. The shrimp and crab cannelloni was great as well!  The chicken parmesan was okay, but the least impressive of the things we ordered. Our server was very cheerful and fun, too!

For those of you who are unfamiliar with the Cuyahoga Valley National Park, it is a SUBURBAN\/RURAL national park. It is NOT what most would consider a "traditional" national park. Tens of thousands of people live within the boundries of the CVNP, with numerous cities, towns, and villiages making up a large percentage of the park land. A percentage of the park land is also shared with the Cleveland Metroparks. For these reasons, the park maps, signs, and borders can be difficult to understand.

Coscto Price Codes:

Prices that end in 97¢: These have been marked down from the regular priced items, which end in 99¢

79¢, 49¢, or 89¢: items that Costco got a deal from the manufacturer. Good deals but not as good as .97

An asterisk* - discontinued 

88¢ or .00 endings: Manager markdowns available only at that store, usually means a good deal
